  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="KT310-kilavi">varaiviṭai muṉintu kiḻatti tōḻikku uraittatu. </p>
        <p xml:lang="en">Told by HER to the confidante, being fed up with
          [awaiting] the time of marriage. </p>
      </div>

      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="KT310">
          <l> puḷḷum pulampiṉa pūvuṅ kūmpiṉa</l>
          <l> kāṉalum pulampunaṉi yuṭaittē vāṉamu</l>
          <l> nammē pōlu mammart tāki</l>
          <l> yellai kaḻiyap pulleṉ ṟaṉṟē</l>
          <l> yiṉṉu muḷeṉē tōḻi yinnilai</l>
          <l> taṇṇiya kamaḻu ñāḻaṟ</l>
          <l> ṟaṇṇan tuṟaivark kuraikkunarp peṟiṉē.</l>
        </lg>

        <lg xml:lang="en">
          <l>The birds began to lament and the flowers closed</l>
          <l>and the seashore grove is filled with loneliness.</l>
          <l rend="indent9">The sky too,</l>
          <l>just like us, <note place="foot"> <term xml:lang="ta"> nammē </term>: here the  <term xml:lang="ta">-ē </term> probably cannot but be understood as kind of emphatic particle.  </note> has become obscure</l>
          <l>[and] empty as the daylight passes.</l>
          <l>Even now I am, friend.</l>
          <l rend="indent6">This state,</l>
          <l>if only <note place="foot"> For <term xml:lang="ta"> peṟiṉē </term> clauses expressing an irreal wish cf. KT 29.7, 136.5.  </note> someone told the man from the cool ghat</l>
          <l>of cool <note place="foot"> <term xml:lang="ta"> taṇṇiya </term> can either be understood as an attribute to <term xml:lang="ta"> ñāral</term>, which would mean to take also the <term xml:lang="ta"> peyareccam kamaḻum </term> as a mere adjective, or it can be an adverb modifying <term xml:lang="ta"> kamaḻum </term>: "cooly smelling". </note> [and] fragrant Ñāḻal trees.</l>

        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
